<TITLE> Polish PM visits troops in Iraq for Christmas </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BAGHDAD, Dec 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Polish Prime Minister Donald Tusk and Defence Minister Bogdan Klich visited their country's 900 troops in Iraq on Wednesday. "They are meeting soldiers for Christmas, to give them their best wishes," Polish military spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Wlodek Glogowski said by telephone from the Polish base, Camp Echo, in Diwaniya, a mainly Shi'ite city south of Baghdad. The two ministers greeted soldiers at the base and were due to fly back to Poland later on Wednesday. Tusk's new centre-right government has pledged to pull the troops out of Iraq by October 2008, clashing with conservative President Lech Kaczynski, who opposes a troop withdrawal so soon. On Tuesday, Tusk's government asked Kaczynski to approve the withdrawal, something Tusk promised last month after defeating Kaczynski's twin brother Jaroslaw in an October election. Poland has been one of Washington's main allies in Iraq and commanded a multi-national division initially responsible for a wide swathe of territory south of Baghdad. The force's size and role have gradually shrunk over the past few yea
